    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-01-08T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-01-08T11:00:00-05:00" n="72"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d72">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/3117</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_EAI1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Elkus</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Constantinople</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-01-08T18:00:00+02:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 8, 1917, 6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received January 10, 8 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2393. <persName>Newbold</persName>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d72fn1">Maj. <persName>Henry L. Newbold</persName>, military
                        attaché at Constantinople.</note> has been informed by the Constantinople
                    military attaché of a neutral power that some German officers just arrived from
                    Berlin have stated to him that Germany is preparing for a <pb facs="0254" n="82"
                        xml:id="pg_82"/> pitiless submarine warfare by the end of February next. The
                    Germans will, it is stated, effectively blockade by their submarines the whole
                    of the British coast and will sink without warning every vessel that goes to or
                    from England. This the Germans state will be a breach of all their promises to
                    such an extent that it will certainly bring about a rupture of diplomatic
                    relations between the United States and Germany, if not war.</p>
                <p>I submit the above to the Department for what it may be worth. It may be that
                    this has been purposely reported to our Embassy in order that it should be
                    transmitted to the Department so as to induce the latter to use all its
                    influence to bring about peace.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_EAI1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Elkus</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
